          "body": "The chapter's central act unfolds at Dothan (37:18-30). The brothers see Joseph 'from a distance' and plot to kill him before he can speak — pure conspiracy, not provocation. Reuben tries a half-measure (throw him in the pit, planning a later rescue, 37:21-22), and Judah negotiates a profit (sell him to the Ishmaelites, 37:26-27). They strip him of the tunic that symbolized the father's love, throw him in a waterless cistern, and — in one of Scripture's most chilling details — *sit down to eat a meal* (37:25) while their brother cries out from the pit (we learn this later from 42:21). The Ishmaelite caravan from Gilead — descendants of Hagar's son (Gen. 16:15) — appears at the precise moment to convert murder into a sale. Twenty shekels of silver (37:28), the standard slave-price for a male age 5-20 (Lev. 27:5), is the price Joseph fetches; the narrator's silence on the sum's significance allows the reader to feel its callousness."
